{"key":"post-10419109","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>10419109</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;Scucci said:&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Yeah, all the rooms in the house were wired for 15A, the room where my games are is the only room that was having issues, so I took it up to 20A, I think that's just getting me by for now...&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Which means your house was wired with #14 wire, which is only rated at 15 amps without overheating.&amp;nbsp; The breaker is sized to protect the wire, so going to a 20 amp breaker means your wire can heat up red hot, melting the insulation, and not trip the breaker.&amp;nbsp; You've created a major fire hazard by changing the breaker to a higher size.&amp;nbsp; There was a recent case in NY State where someone did that and burned the house down, killing two children.&amp;nbsp; In addition to losing his kids, the guy was charged with negligent homicide and went to jail.&amp;nbsp; I'd suggest running a larger wire if you're using a larger breaker.&amp;nbsp; It could save your life.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>10419150</next>\n<prev>10419068</prev>\n<first>10418417</first>\n<last>10424100</last>\n<when>1243617731</when>\n<utime>05/29/09 08:22 PM</utime>\n</post>"}